RP ROLE-PLAYING IN-CHARACTER OUT-OF-CHARACTER

@Yd20MUD: Age of Dragons@n is a role playing expected MUD.  That means we expect
people to role play, but do not punish those who don't as long as they use the
proper communication channels for their out of character communication, and do
not disrupt or disturb the role playing of others.

What do we consider role playing?  We consider role playing to be the taking on
of a fictional and original character in the Dragonlance universe and
acting as if you were that person as you play the game.  For example, a qualinesti
elf might role play as an orphan whose parents were killed by goblins in a raid on
their village.  After living alone in the wild for some time, he happened upon
a human village who he eventually befriended.  From there he made a life as a
ranger assisting the humans until they too were slaughtered by goblins.  Fearing
the harm that could come from further attacks he went out into the world to
learn and grow so that one day he could stop the goblin hordes from any more massacres.

This is one example of a character you create but the possibilities are endless.
Remember that whatever character you create, he or she is a real person, with real
strengths and weaknesses, virtues and flaws, and a real personality, potentially
quite different from your own.

The other thing that needs clarification is the difference between in character
and out of character.

In character is your state of play when you are acting as your character and not
speaking as the person at the computer.  You should only use information that your
character would know, and communicate in a way that makes sense.  For example,
you know the other character at the bar is your friend, but your character doesn't.
You should try to act out a role playing scenario in which the two characters meet
and discover a reason why they should go adventuring together.  Also, regarding item
stats remember that your character doesn't know that an item is +1 or +2 or +10.
All he knows is that it is magical, and to what general degree.  So use the proper
words to explain magical effects.  For example a +5 flaming long sword might be
explained as "a long sword with a powerful magical enchantment whose blade may be
engulfed in flames that harm enemies but not the owner".  Be creative and simply
make your best attempt.  We are more worried about the existance of role play than
the quality thereof.

Out of character communication, by contrast, is when you are speaking about things
only you, the real person at the computer, knows.  Stuff about the real world, game
stats and other game topics your character doesn't know, and in essence, anything
that you wouldn't see a character in a Dragonlance novel say or do, should
be said on an out of character channel.

In Character Channels Include: rsay, rgsay, shout, emote, socials, mail
Out of Character Channels Include: ooc, gsay, chat, newbie, socials, mail, tell
guildchat, clantalk, emotes (outside of taverns only)

If you have any questions about role playing, please post your question on our forums
and we will answer it as promptly and as best we can.


