CHARACTER-CREATION CHARACTER-GENERATION

Our character creation system is one of the best things we have going
for us.  But unfortunately, for a new character, it can be a bit imposing
and time consuming, given the amount of choices available.  It is especially
difficult for someone who is not well versed on D&&D and even for those that
are, there is enough different with our MUD that such knowledge isn't going
to garauntee easy choices.

With that said let's walk you through character creation.  It is assumed by
now that you have chosen a name and a gender and are in the game.  Your first
task is to read the rules of the mud.  This only needs to be done once per
account, so make sure you at least glance over them, and make a note to go
back and fully read them during your first week of playing here.
The next step is to choose a race.  Each race has certain benefits and
disadvantages, and some are clearly advantageous for specific builds over
others.  Please note that there are some races, advanced races, which cost
account experience, and can only be chosen by experienced players who have
proven themselves to staff as beneficial players to the MUD in some way.

If a help entry is not available for your race, try searching for it on the
web.  All of our races use stock D&&D 3.5e rules so if we haven't gotten around
to adding the help for it (and we will!), then the information is still out
there.

Next step is stat selection.  This is an important phase.  Generally speaking
it costs 1 point to go up to 15, 2 for 16, 3 for 17 and 4 for 18.  Racial
modifiers are added when you select your class.  Every stat has a use in this
game, though as always, some are better for certain builds than others.

After stat selection you must select your description.  This is what people
see in place of your name when they do not know your character.  It is
dynamically generated and is based on your gender, race, and various adjectives
you use to describe your person.

Finally, with this done, the last step is to select your class and spend your
intial skill and feat points.
For skills you can get a basic idea of what each skill does by typing
'HELP QUICK SKILL DESCS'.  

For feats you can get an idea of what each feat does by typing 'HELP FEATS' 
and reading the information there, but specifically the 'FEATS AVAILABLE DESC'
command will display all feats that you can take with a short description of 
what that feat does.

And that about wraps up character creation.  If you find yourself in need of
more help, feel free to ask another player or imm on the newbie or chat channels.

